        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To normalize pdf-like documents (.djvu) into the PDF format via the ddjvu utility, providing a uniform input format for downstream PDF readers. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  PDF-like document format normalization via ddjvu. \par \b Input\/ \:  Files with pdf-like extensions or MIME types (e.g. .djvu). \par \b Output\/ \:  Converted .pdf file path. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(9): ddjvu (DjVuLibre); READS_DATA_FROM(7): <ref refid="namespacededoc_1_1extensions_1aac3b199243c8795f127aefef6c73fa04" kindref="member">dedoc.extensions.converted_extensions</ref>] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>convert() always invokes ddjvu with <ndash/>format=pdf.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Output file path is always {dir}/{name_wo_ext}.pdf. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why ddjvu instead of a Python library? A: ddjvu is the reference DjVu-to-PDF converter from the DjVuLibre project. No pure-Python equivalent exists. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 — Added semantic markup and LDD logging] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Converts pdf-like formats to PDF via ddjvu] =&gt; PDFConverter \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[PDFConverter.convert]: User (Upload) → NormalizeToPdf → PdfFileReady </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
